<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
  <div class="faq-q">Can airlines actually arrest me for skiplagging?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">No. Skiplagging is not a crime. It is a violation of the airline's contract of carriage, which is a private agreement, not a law. The worst they can do is cancel your other tickets, void your miles, or ban you from future bookings.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <div class="faq-q">Will the airline charge me extra at the gate if they catch me?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">They can require you to pay the difference between your hidden city fare and the direct fare to your true destination. Some airlines have started doing this proactively when they suspect skiplagging. Always be prepared to walk away from the booking rather than pay the upcharge.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <div class="faq-q">Does hidden city ticketing work on international flights?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">Yes, but with more complications. You may face visa requirements for the ticketed final destination (even though you won't fly there), and customs procedures at the layover can be slower. Domestic hidden city is much easier than international.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <div class="faq-q">What happens if my flight is delayed and I miss the layover deplane window?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">If the connecting flight to your ticketed destination is also delayed, you can still get off. If your connection is moved earlier or rerouted, your plan fails. Build buffer time into your hidden city itineraries when possible.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <div class="faq-q">Can I do this with award tickets (points/miles)?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">Technically yes, but the risk-reward is much worse. Airlines monitor award redemptions more closely, and detection means losing not just status but the underlying miles. Don't skiplag on award tickets.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <div class="faq-q">Does Skiplagged.com still work after the lawsuit?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">Yes. The May 2025 ruling confirmed that the underlying booking practice is legal. Skiplagged continues operating its core service. The lawsuit affected how they can use American Airlines' branding, not whether they can find these fares.</div>
</div>

<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

<p>Hidden city ticketing is a legal, real way to save 40-60% on the right flights. It's not a magic trick that works for every trip — it works on specific routes, under specific conditions, with specific rules. Follow the carry-on, one-way, and no-elite-status rules, and the strategy is sound. Ignore them, and the consequences are real.</p>

<p>Most travelers don't need to skiplag every trip. But knowing this option exists — and when to use it — adds another tool to your kit for finding cheap flights.</p>

